    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-02-09T19:20:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-02-09T19:20:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <head>329. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d329fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 6 <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIC1">CHICOM</gloss>. Limited Official Use. Repeated to
                        Taipei, Hong Kong, Bujumbura, Mogadiscio, Tokyo, London, Paris, and
                        Rome.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-02-10T00:20:00+00:00">February 10, 1971,
                        0020Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>390. Subj: <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> in <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>As expected, <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss> Farah (Somalia) raised
                            <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> on point of order at beginning
                        of first <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> meeting of 1971. His speech was
                        carefully reasoned but pro-forma attack on right of <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                            >GRC</gloss> to represent China in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>.
                        Reps of Syria, <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>, France, Poland and
                        Italy spoke in support of Farah and Burundi would have but did not since
                            <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TN1">Terence</persName> away from <gloss
                            target="#t_NY1">NY</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> and US
                        spoke in rebuttal.</item>
                    <pb facs="0628" n="591" xml:id="pg_591"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Farah’s statement expressed his <gloss target="#t_DEL1">del</gloss>’s
                        “strong objections” to acceptance of credentials of <gloss target="#t_AMB1"
                            >Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName> (<gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                            >GRC</gloss>) and recalled Algerian move to have <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                            >SC</gloss> consider credentials of all <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                            >SC</gloss> members in 1968. However, he made no procedural moves,
                        simply expressing desire to return to the matter “at a future date, after
                        consulting like-minded delegations”.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Remainder of Farah speech was routine re-hashing of arguments that <gloss
                            target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> has no right to sit in <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and attempt to refute arguments that <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> did not want or was not fit for <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> membership. Farah spoke confidently of
                        growing awareness of injustice being done to <gloss target="#t_PRC1"
                            >PRC</gloss>, which applied to take China seat as early as 1949. He
                        referred to passage of <gloss target="#t_IQ1">IQ</gloss> as dishonest
                        procedural device to thwart will of <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                        majority and quoted statement by Senator McGovern as evidence of growing
                        public demand for new approach to <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>
                        problem.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Speaking as President of Council, <persName corresp="#p_YCW1"
                            >Yost</persName> “took note” of Farah’s statement and said his govt’s
                        position would be reflected in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> records.
                        Reverting to role as US Rep, <persName corresp="#p_YCW1">Yost</persName>
                        totally rejected as unfounded Farah’s allegations concerning so-called US
                        aggression in Indochina.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TGJ1">Tomeh</persName> (Syria) said he was in full
                        agreement with Farah’s remarks and agreed that <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                            >GRC</gloss> Rep’s credentials subject to objection under <gloss
                            target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> rules of procedure.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName>Malik</persName> (<gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>) made
                        brief, pro-forma statement along lines of his last-minute intervention on
                            <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> at 25th <gloss target="#t_GA1"
                            >GA</gloss>. He said <gloss target="#t_SOV1">Sov</gloss> position on
                            <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> “well-known and unchanged” and
                        called for <gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> expulsion from all <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> organs.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KMJ1">Kosciusko-Morizet</persName> (France) briefly
                        said he fully shared views of Farah and had no doubt Chinese seat belonged
                        to <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KE1">Kulaga</persName> (Poland) chimed in with
                        statement which appeared more enthusiastic than
                        <persName>Malik</persName>’s.</item>
                    <label>9.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VP1">Vinci</persName> (Italy) simply noted that
                            “<gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> shares views of previous speakers
                        on <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> in <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                            >UN</gloss>”.</item>
                    <label>10.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName> (China) made relatively mild
                        statement arguing that <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> not place for
                            <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss> debate and affirming that <gloss
                            target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> is authentic voice of people of
                        China.</item>
                    <label>11.</label>
                    <item>Speaking as Representative of US, <persName corresp="#p_YCW1"
                            >Yost</persName> gave statement prepared by <gloss target="#t_DEPT1"
                            >Dept</gloss> stating that <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName>’s
                        credentials approved in 1962 and not objected to since, and recalling <gloss
                            target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> Res 396 (V) pointing out that <gloss
                            target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> was proper place to discuss <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>12.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Comment:</hi> As Farah is aware that he does not have the
                        votes to carry procedural motion on <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>
                        in present <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>, we expect we have heard last
                        of this question for a time.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_YCW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Yost</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
